The causes of deaths of the bovine animals in the reported areas were
nitrogen poisoning and foot-and-mouth disease (FMD), as revealed by
the results of laboratory testing, according to the news report
above.

FMD is a highly infectious viral disease, and the disease is endemic
in India. Bovine animals are vaccinated twice a year in the country to
protect them from being affected with the disease. As suspected, the
animals died might have not been timely vaccinated against the
disease.

Whether the animals also suffered from nitrogen poisoning needs to be
ascertained carefully, because in a similar epidemiological situation,
as described in the article, animals could also predispose to nitrate
poisoning.

"Nitrate poisoning (toxicosis) in animals (especially ruminants)
results from excess consumption of nitrates from plants or water or
via ingestion of nitrate-containing fertilizers. The nitrate ion
(NO3-) is reduced to nitrite ion (NO2-), which is rapidly absorbed and
leads to the formation of methemoglobin, which inhibits oxygen
transport. This results in dyspnea, cyanotic mucous membranes,
weakness, and, if severe, death due to anoxia. Ruminants are more
susceptible because rumen flora can rapidly reduce nitrates to
nitrites. Methylene blue, administered IV, will reverse the
methemoglobinemia and may be effective as a treatment with supportive
care. Ocular fluid specimens are most appropriate sample for
postmortem, with laboratory testing of suspected sources of nitrate
exposure."
(<https://www.msdvetmanual.com/toxicology/nitrate-and-nitrite-poisoning/nit=
rate-and-nitrite-poisoning-in-animals>)

"Non protein nitrogen (NPN) poisoning (toxicosis) results from
excessive consumption of sources of NPN or urea. It is acute and often
rapidly fatal, with clinical signs including muscle tremors, abdominal
pain, incoordination, respiratory distress, and recumbency, then
death. Diagnosis can be made by analysis of postmortem samples for
ammonia content and of suspected sources for non protein nitrogen
content; ruminal pH > 7.5 is supportive of the diagnosis. Treatment
includes removal of suspected source materials, ruminal infusion of
acetic acid and cold water, as well as supportive therapy."
(<https://www.msdvetmanual.com/toxicology/nonprotein-nitrogen-poisoning/non=
protein-nitrogen-poisoning-in-animals>)

Bathinda district is a district in the Malwa region of Punjab, India.
(<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bathinda_district>) - Mod.PKB

