medmail.org/?lang=3Dsoas</a>.=0D<br>=0D<br>The causes of deaths of the bovi=
ne animals in the reported areas were<br>nitrogen poisoning and foot-and-mo=
uth disease (FMD), as revealed by<br>the results of laboratory testing, acc=
ording to the news report<br>above.=0D<br>=0D<br>FMD is a highly infectious=
 viral disease, and the disease is endemic<br>in India. Bovine animals are =
vaccinated twice a year in the country to<br>protect them from being affect=
ed with the disease. As suspected, the<br>animals died might have not been =
timely vaccinated against the<br>disease.=0D<br>=0D<br>Whether the animals =
also suffered from nitrogen poisoning needs to be<br>ascertained carefully,=
 because in a similar epidemiological situation,<br>as described in the art=
icle, animals could also predispose to nitrate<br>poisoning.=0D<br>=0D<br>"=
Nitrate poisoning (toxicosis) in animals (especially ruminants)<br>results =
from excess consumption of nitrates from plants or water or<br>via ingestio=
n of nitrate-containing fertilizers. The nitrate ion<br>(NO3-) is reduced t=
o nitrite ion (NO2-), which is rapidly absorbed and<br>leads to the formati=
on of methemoglobin, which inhibits oxygen<br>transport. This results in dy=
spnea, cyanotic mucous membranes,<br>weakness, and, if severe, death due to=
 anoxia. Ruminants are more<br>susceptible because rumen flora can rapidly =
reduce nitrates to<br>nitrites. Methylene blue, administered IV, will rever=
se the<br>methemoglobinemia and may be effective as a treatment with suppor=
tive<br>care. Ocular fluid specimens are most appropriate sample for<br>pos=
tmortem, with laboratory testing of suspected sources of nitrate<br>exposur=
e."<br>(<a href=3D"https://u19268662.ct.sendgrid.net/ss/c/TLh_csrC34X_iXpbY=
